    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1816103568" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1816103568" />
    <a title="Michael Finocchiaro" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/48483884-michael-finocchiaro"><img alt="Michael Finocchiaro" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1576692048p2/48483884.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1816103568?book_show_action=true">Nov 11, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael Finocchiaro" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael Finocchiaro" href="/user/show/48483884-michael-finocchiaro">Michael Finocchiaro</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780002717458" href="/book/show/40741.The_Sportswriter">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/48483884-michael-finocchiaro?shelf=novels">novels</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/48483884-michael-finocchiaro?shelf=american-20th-c">american-20th-c</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/48483884-michael-finocchiaro?shelf=pulitzer-fiction">pulitzer-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/48483884-michael-finocchiaro?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1816103568" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11057102614481854199">Richard Ford&apos;s <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40722.The_Sportswriter' title='The Sportswriter by Richard Ford' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Sportswriter</a> is the first of his series about the character Frank Boscombe, the second of which, <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/12374.Independence_Day' title='Independence Day by Richard Ford' rel='nofollow noopener'>Independence Day</a> won the Pulitzer in 1996. <u>The Sportswriter</u> was written in 1985 and introduces us to a self-proclaimed <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/169718.Babbitt' title='Babbitt by Sinclair Lewis' rel='nofollow noopener'>Babbitt</a> (from the classic Sinclair Lewis novel of 1922) from which it borrows a bit of the style, but is entirely written from the perspective of and in the voice of the protagonist, a 39 year old divorcee with two kids who are alive and one, still very present, de</span>
  <span id="freeText11057102614481854199" style="display:none">Richard Ford's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40722.The_Sportswriter" title="The Sportswriter by Richard Ford" rel="nofollow noopener">The Sportswriter</a> is the first of his series about the character Frank Boscombe, the second of which, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/12374.Independence_Day" title="Independence Day by Richard Ford" rel="nofollow noopener">Independence Day</a> won the Pulitzer in 1996. <u>The Sportswriter</u> was written in 1985 and introduces us to a self-proclaimed <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/169718.Babbitt" title="Babbitt by Sinclair Lewis" rel="nofollow noopener">Babbitt</a> (from the classic Sinclair Lewis novel of 1922) from which it borrows a bit of the style, but is entirely written from the perspective of and in the voice of the protagonist, a 39 year old divorcee with two kids who are alive and one, still very present, dead son. It is set in suburban New Jersey, as Frank finds that Gotham is just too big for him and prefers mediocrity to standing out. He is in an informal club, The Divorced Men's Club, which meets regularly for beers and conversations on anything other than their failed marriages. <b>"In a way, I suppose, you could say all of it were and are lost, and know it, and we simply try to settle into our lostness as comfortably and with as much good manners and little curiosity as we can. "</b> (p. 86) When this taboo about "little curiosity" is broken during the book, things go very wrong as things do later in the book. Yet, there is already a sense of disequiblibrium in all the combined dreaminess of the group: <b>"Dreamy people actually have little to offer one another, tend in fact to neutralize each other's dreaminess in bleary nugatude."</b> (-. 88). This is actually a rather fitting description of gatherings of men that I have been a part of on occasion myself.<br /><br />The America Ford describes is still in the grips of Reaganomics with the fragile advances of the 60s and 70s starting to unroll a bit. Frank speaks, in a tone I recognize from having been a teenager at that time, in the voice of what could have been my father, about the changes in his own life over a period of roughly 72 hours from the anniversary of his son's death to Easter Sunday during which most of the action in the novel takes place. We learn about his dreaminess which is partially to blame for his destroyed marriage. <b>"Dreaminess is, among other things, a state of suspended recognition, and a response to too much useless and complicated factuality. Its symptoms can be a long-term interest in the weather, or a sustained soaring feeling, or a bout of the stares that you sometimes caan not even know about except in retrospect when things are fogged."</b> (p. 48) It is this malaise that we live in during the book where he is incapable to talking about - or, indeed, even being in touch with - his feelings and this distance between what he wants to do and what he actually does which is typically a half-effort. <br /><br />Frank was a promising writer, but decided to become a sportswriter instead allowing him the freedom to travel. <b>"One thing certain is that I had somehow lost my sense of anticipation at age 25. Anticipation is the sweet pain to know whatever's next - a must for any writer. And I had no more interest in what happened next - the next sentence, the next day - than I cared what a rock weighed on Mars."</b> (p. 49) During this period, his oldest son Ralph contracts Reyes disease, for which we still in 2019 do not know the cause, and dies at only 14 - a devastating loss for the family which Frank deals with by delving deeper into his "dreaminess". <br /><br />At the beginning of the novel, we are at the cemetery close to Frank's house in which his dead son is buried and we meet his ex-wife named X throughout the book. We realize that Frank actually still harbors feelings for her, but his dreaminess prevents him from expressing it in a way that will reach over the gulf between the two of them. Frank then goes with girlfriend and nurse Vicki to Detroit. Before leaving, however, he has a meeting of the Divorced Men's Club after which one member, Walter, who's wife took off to Bimini with her lover, confesses having had a homosexual encounter a few days before and feels a bit guilty about it. Given that this is 1985 and homosexuality is still socially unaccepted, it is understandable that Walter would be stressed out. Frank, of course, is only capable of murmuring some placitudes as he wants to get going and is uncomfortable with the confession. <br /><b>"What's friendship's realest measure?<br />I'll tell you. The amount of precious time you'll squander on someone else's calamites and fuckups."</b> (p. 103). <br /><br />After this encounter, Frank stakes out his ex-wife's house wondering if he should go in and see his kids or not. His son Paul comes out of the house and releases a pigeon named Vassar and then notices his father and comes over to talk to him. <br /><b>"When's Ole Vassar reporting back?"<br />"He isn't. I told him he could live in Cape May."<br />"Why is that?"<br />"Because Ralph's dead. I think."</b> (p. 116)<br />I really enjoyed this image and this small conversation about their grief and how they dance around it. It felt quite real.<br /><br />Frank and Vicki touch down in Detroit. His description of arrival feels familiar to me:<br /><b>"And what did I feel exactly at this debarking moment?<br />At least a hundred things at once, all competing to take the moment and make it their own, reduce dramatic life to a gritty, knowable kernel.<br />This is, of course, a minor but pernicious lie of literature, that at times like these, after significant or disappointing divulgences, at arrivals or departures of obvious important, when touchdowns are scored, knock-outs recorded, loved one buried, orgasms notches, that at such times we are any of us altogether <i>in</i> an emotion that we are within ourselves and not able to detect other emotions we might also be feeling, or be about to feel, or prefer to feel.</b> (p. 125). <br />Again, I can definitely relate to this inability to sort through and prioritize my own emotions and take into account their complexity and interactions with the emotions of those around me. I suppose that perhaps both Frank and I lack what is called these days, emotional intelligence, as it was clearly not something I learned at home from a healthy father figure. <br /><br />In Detroit, Frank is supposed to interview a former NFL player who is paralyzed below the waist due to an accident. This interview goes poorly. As for Vicki and Frank, there is a discomfort between them that starts to grow. Frank insists on saying "I love you", but other than a few tumbles in the sack, "boinking" in Frank's terminology, the distance between them increases. He muses about whether he can say "I love you" to Vicky and tries to touch on his emotional core:<br /><b>"When you are fully in your emotions, when they are simple and appealing enough to be in, aand the distance is closed between what you feel and what you might <i>also</i> feel, then your instincts can be trusted. It is the difference between a man who quits his job to become a fishing guide on Lake Big Trout, and one who one day as he paddles his canoe into the dock at dusk stops paddling to admire the sunset and realizes how much he wants to be a guide on Lake Big Trout, and another man who has made the same decision stopped paddling at the same time, felt how glad he was, but also thought he could probably also be a guide on Windigo Lake if he decided to, and might also get a better deal on canoes."</b> (p 127). Frank is clearly in the third category there.<br /><br />There is a falling out between them and he ponders the phrase "What's the matter?":<br /><b>"...I wonder, in fact, how many times I have said that or something equal to it to a woman passing palely through my life. <i>What're you thinking? What's made you so quiet? You seem suddenly different. What's the matter"</i> Love <i>me</i> is what this means, of course, Or, at least, second best: surrender. Or at the <i>very</i> least, take some time regaling me in why you won't, and maybe by the end you will.</b> (p. 177). Frank clearly cannot truly say "I love you" and feel it sincerely and this precipates the end of this relationship.<br /><br />They take an earlier flight home to New Jersey, but after Frank drops her off - no kiss - Walter from the Divorced Men's Club is in his living room, having mistaken Frank's African boarder for a butler and had himself let in. He is in a state: <b>"In all likelihood, it is the same suit of casual clothes Walter has worn since his Grinnell days. Only behind his tortoise-shells, his eyes look vanquished, and his slick, bond-salesman's hair could stand a washing. Walter looks, in other words, like private death, though I have a feeling he is here to share some of it with me.</b> (p. 187)<br /><br />I won't spoil the rest of the story for you. Things accelerate towards the end and there is a curious denouement and epilogue as well. <br /><br />I enjoyed this book. It is certainly a product of its times, with a vague anti-Semitism and an only half-formed racial conscience as well as an 80s variety of misogyny, but it is a sincere book where the author is probably working through his own emotional quagmire as he describes Frank. I am impatient to read <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/12374.Independence_Day" title="Independence Day by Richard Ford" rel="nofollow noopener">Independence Day</a> to see what happens to Frank Bascomb next. I will also probably delve into a comparison of Frank Boscomb with other middle-American male protagonists such as Philp Roth's Nathan Zuckerman, John Updike's Rabbit Angstrom and Richard Russo's Donald "Sully" Sullivan because each of them comes from the Pennsylvania-New Jersey-New York area and they all are both similar and different and the subject of books that span a few decades of their lives.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11057102614481854199" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

